<subSubSection pageId="826" pageNumber="827" type="reference_group">
<paragraph pageId="826" pageNumber="827">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chaudoir" authorityYear="1877" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Tecnophilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="826" pageNumber="827" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Tecnophilus</taxonomicName>
Chaudoir, 1877: 239. Type species: 
<taxonomicName class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Calleida" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="826" pageNumber="827" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="croceicollis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="826" pageNumber="827">Calleida croceicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken originalValue="Ménétriés">Menetries</normalizedToken>
, 1843 designated by Larson (1969: 44). Etymology. Anagram of the generic name 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Philotecnus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="826" pageNumber="827" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="826" pageNumber="827">Philotecnus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, derived from the Greek 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="826" pageNumber="827">tecnon</emphasis>
(child, young) and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="826" pageNumber="827">philos</emphasis>
(beloved), although Chaudoir was aware that there was no data suggesting that adults of these species care for their young (&quot; 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="826" pageNumber="827">
quoique 
<normalizedToken originalValue="l’amour">l'amour</normalizedToken>
de ces insectes pour leur 
<normalizedToken originalValue="progéniture">progeniture</normalizedToken>
ne soit rien moins que 
<normalizedToken originalValue="prouvé">prouve</normalizedToken>
</emphasis>
&quot;) [masculine].
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="826" pageNumber="827" type="diversity">
<paragraph pageId="826" pageNumber="827">Diversity.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="826" pageNumber="827">Two Nearctic species, one of them extending into northern Mexico.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="826" pageNumber="827" type="identification">
